,"Results in wrist drop"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUlnar tunnel syndrome involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompression in Guyon\u0027s canal\u003C/strong\u003E, which is located at the wrist. This condition involves symptoms such as weakness in the intrinsic muscles of the hand and sensory loss in the ulnar distribution of the palm due to compression of the ulnar nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvolves the dorsal cutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The dorsal cutaneous branch of the ulnar nerve is not affected in Guyon\u0027s canal syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAffects the radial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The ulnar nerve, not the radial nerve, is compressed in this condition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauses sensory loss in the thumb\u003C/strong\u003E - The ulnar nerve does not supply the thumb; it supplies the little finger and half of the ring finger\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResults in wrist drop\u003C/strong\u003E - Wrist drop is associated with injury to the radial nerve injury, not the ulnar nerve \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ulnar tunnel syndrome, also known as Guyon\u0027s canal syndrome, involves compression of the ulnar nerve at the wrist.","The ulnar nerve in Guyon\u0027s canal does not affect the dorsal cutaneous branch, which supplies sensation to the dorsal aspect of the hand.","Symptoms of ulnar tunnel syndrome include weakness in the intrinsic muscles of the hand and sensory loss in the ulnar distribution of the palm."],"references":["Bachoura A, Jacoby SM. Ulnar tunnel syndrome. Orthop Clin North Am. 2012 Oct;43(4):467-74. doi: 10.1016/j.ocl.2012.07.016. PMID: 23026462.","Genova 